Why Madam, replied Lucy, I believe he
thought your Ladyſhip had ſent him an Anſwer;
for he kiſſed the Letter ſeveral times.

I ſhall do all that I ought, anſwered Arabella;
but my Care for the Safety of other Perſons muſt
not make me forget what I owe to my own.

Indeed but it is, Lady Bella, interrupted he;
for if I knew how to pleaſe you, I would never,
if I could help it, offend: Therefore, I beg you,
tell me how I have diſobliged you; for, certainly,
you have treated me as harſhly as if I had been
guilty of ſome very terrible Offence.

Since Love is not voluntary, replied Arabella,
I am not obliged to any Perſon for loving me;
for, queſtionleſs, if he could help it, he would.

The Marquis coming in interrupted Arabella;
upon which ſhe took Occaſion to retire;
leaving Glanville more captivated with her than
ever.

You may do as you will, ſaid the Marquis;
but I think it encouraging her in her Follies to
give them to her again.

Not I indeed, Madam, replied Miſs Glanville;
I know nothing about her; but I ſuppoſe
ſhe is a Jew, by her outlandiſh Name.

Indeed but ſhe did tho', reſumed Arabella;
for ſhe refuſed to give him a glorious Scarf
which ſhe wore, tho' he begged it on his Knees.

Mr. Glanville was ready to die with Vexation,
at the Charmer of his Soul's being thus expoſed;
but there was no Help for it.

Indeed, Madam, I did not, reſumed Lucy;
but he ſeemed to be very ſorry; and ſaid, He
would go and look for your Ladyſhip.

If Mr. Glanville, interrupted Arabella, hopes
for my Pardon, he muſt purchaſe it by his Repentance,
and a ſincere Confeſſion of his Fault;
which you may much better underſtand from
himſelf, than from me: And, for this Purpoſe,
I will condeſcend to grant him a private Audience,
at which I deſire you would be preſent;
and alſo, I ſhould take it well, if you will let
him know, that he owes this Favour wholly to
your Interpoſition.

Sir George, though he really admired Arabella,
was not ſo paſſionately in Love as Mr. Glanville;
and, being a keen Sportſman, eagerly purſued


the Game, with the reſt of the Hunters;
but Mr. Glanville minded nothing but his Couſin,
and kept cloſe by her.

I may command him to live, ſaid Arabella;
and there is no Queſtion but he would
obey me, if I likewiſe permit him to love me;
but, this laſt not being fit for me to do, I ſee
no way to prevent the ſad Reſolution he has
taken.
